In Byzantium, the central structure is considered archetypical. This study shows that this assumption is only partly true. It presents the basilicas of the 7th to 15th centuries, addressing questions of typology, appointments, function, and the relationship to longitudinal and central constructions. It shows that the Byzantines were more flexible in their approach to these construction types than previously assumed, a conclusion supported by theological evidence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecture, Byzantine. 0aBasilicaszByzantine Empire. 4aArchitektur. 4aBasilika. 4aLiturgie. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aBasilica.  aarchitecture.  aliturgy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET ALTERTUMSWISS. 2013z9783110317091oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311026502640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110310351zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110310351zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110310351/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGDb2013  aZDB-23-DGGb2013  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014  aZDB-23-GOA